Your A entity is incorrectly mapping &quot;id_a&quot; in the B table multiple times. Assuming you want your B entity as it is so that it references A, A would need to look like:


    @Entity
    @Table(name = &quot;a&quot;)
    public class A {
    
        @Id
        @Column(name = &quot;id&quot;)
        private String id;
    
        @OneToMany(mappedBy=&quot;a&quot;, fetch = FetchType.LAZY, cascade = CascadeType.ALL, orphanRemoval = true)
        private List&lt;B&gt; firstValuesB;
    }

Now when you save(a) you&#39;ll have to remember that B.a controls the foreign key and must be set or the fk will be null:

    A a = new A();
    B b = new B();
    b.setA(a);
    a.setFirstValuesB(new ArrayList()).add(b);
    save(a);

Both sides should be set in your relationship to match what it is in the database or you will run into issues.

